{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508114","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508114"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:02:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:02:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2718"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2718","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2718"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.08,0.04,0.8,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2718"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78814"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2718","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2718"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2718"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64163"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1221"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3430"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3448"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27024"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42555"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78814","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78814"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 37-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner concerned about a rash that has developed on her cheeks. She notices she becomes flushed and red across her cheeks several times per day and it is made worse by hot tea and spicy food. She does not have any other symptoms such as fatigue, weight loss or joint pain. She is otherwise in good health and no medical history of note. She does not take any medications and has no allergies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe uses a daily moisturiser on her face morning and night, which she has been using for over two years. She washes her face with water to remove her mineral make-up each night.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination she is a Fitzpatrick type 1. Her cheeks are erythematous, with prominent blood vessels and there are multiple small red pustules clustered around her nasolabial folds. There are no other rashes on her body or face.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Seborrheic dermatitis","Periorificial dermatitis","Systemic lupus erythematosus","Rosacea","Irritant contact dermatitis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe stem describes a typical presentation of \u003Cstrong\u003Erosacea\u003C/strong\u003E. Rosacea is a common condition that causes frequent blushing/flushing of the face, it can progress to a point where the face remains persistently red due to prominent blood vessels called telangiectasia. It is commonly worsened or triggered by factors such as hot drinks, alcohol and spicy food, as well as sun exposure. The small papules or pustules across the nose, forehead, cheeks and/or chin are also a common feature of the condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeborrheic dermatitis\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by erythematous, scaly patches, often with a greasy appearance, typically affecting areas rich in sebaceous glands such as the scalp, face, and upper trunk. It does not typically cause flushing or pustules as seen in rosacea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESystemic lupus erythematosus (SLE)\u003C/strong\u003E classically features a butterfly rash across the cheeks and it can be the first indication of SLE in 25% of cases. This is often photo-sensitive meaning it develops after exposure to the sun. This rash is described as papular erythema that resembles a viral exanthem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeriorificial dermatitis\u003C/strong\u003E affects the peri-oral area, chin, eyelids, perinasal area, but typically spares the cheeks and forehead. The rash presents with groups of small red papules and is itchy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIrritant contact dermatitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a condition where the skin reacts to triggers such as over-exposure to water, chemicals, materials, or weather changes. The products that she uses on her face are unlikely to be causing an irritant dermatitis, as she has used them for many years, and she only uses water once per day to clean her make-up off. It is rare for adults to have contact irritant dermatitis on the face, as this most commonly affects children/toddlers where the saliva and dribble is the irritant. The rash is usually confined to the area that is exposed and does not come and go as described by the stem. \u00a0\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Rosacea causes flushing of the cheeks/face and prominent blood vessels (telangiectasia) can be seen","Rosacea should NOT be treated with topical steroids, but rather topical antibiotics or laser in some cases"],"references":["Litchman G, Nair PA, Atwater AR, et al. Contact Dermatitis. [Updated 2023 Sep 4]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459230/","Farshchian M, Daveluy S. Rosacea. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557574/","Vale ECSD, Garcia LC. Cutaneous lupus erythematosus: a review of etiopathogenic, clinical, diagnostic and therapeutic aspects. An Bras Dermatol. 2023 May-Jun;98(3):355-372. doi: 10.1016/j.abd.2022.09.005. Epub 2023 Mar 1. PMID: 36868923; PMCID: PMC10173173. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36868923/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64163"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2718"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64163"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T19:31:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T19:33:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2718"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78814"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suit